title: Experimental study of the excitation functions of deuteron induced reactions on natSn up to 40 MeV

x4freetext: Experimental study of the excitation functions of
deuteron induced reactions on natSn up to 40 MeV

x4codes.hlp: Institute for Nuclear Research (ATOMKI), Debrecen, Hungary

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Nucl. Instrum. Methods in Physics Res., Sect.B, Vol.269, p.405 (2011)

x4freetext: 21 MeV
40 MeV
Natural high-purity Sn foils (Goodfellow >99%) were
assembled together with interleaved degrader and
monitor foils.
Foil thickness: 12 micron at VUB and 7 micron at TOH.
Two stacks were irradiated with deuteron beams.
Deuteron beam energy: 21 MeV and 40 MeV,
beam intensity: 150 nA and 80 nA,
irradiation time: 1 hour and 30 min
at VUB (Vrije Univeriteit Brussels, Belgium) and
at TOH (Tohoku University, Japan), respectively.
The energy of the extracted beam was determined
by calibrated magnetic bending at TOH and
by calibrated parameters of the beam extraction at VUB.
Irradiations took place in Faraday-cup like or
isolated target holders for rough beam intensity
control.
Measurements of the induced activity started shortly
after end of bombardment at VUB while a cooling period
of at least a day was left due to the high initial
activity at TOH.
No chemical separation was done and measurements were
repeated several times for weeks.
Degrader and monitor foils:
Ti 12 micron at VUB and
Al 100 micron, Ta 25 micron at TOH.

The energy degradation along the stack was calculated
on the basis of this polynomial approximation.
The decay data of the contributing reactions were
taken from NuDat2.5 database.
The uncertainty on the primary incident
energy is estimated to be 0.1 MeV which increases to
2 MeV on the last foil due to cumulative effects.

x4freetext: The uncertainty on cross-section was
estimated taking into account uncertainties of the
following linearly contributing processes with equal
weight:
target non-uniformity (3%),
incident particle intensity (7%),
detection efficiency (5%),
determination of the peak areas
including statistical errors (1-5%),
absolute abundance of the used gamma rays (1-5%).
The total resulting uncertainty amounts to 10-13%
obtained by quadratic summation of the contributing
sources.
